# CODEOWNERS — Safety-Critical Software Repository
#
# This file defines who must review changes to each path before a pull request
# can be merged. GitHub enforces these rules when "Require review from Code Owners"
# is enabled in branch protection settings.
#
# Syntax:
#   <path-pattern>  <owner> [<owner> ...]
#
# Owners can be GitHub usernames (@username), team slugs (@org/team-name), or
# email addresses. Teams must have read access to the repository.
#
# The LAST matching rule for a file wins. Order rules from most general (top)
# to most specific (bottom) so that specific rules override general ones.
#
# Documentation: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners

# =============================================================================
# GLOBAL OWNERS
# =============================================================================
# Every file in the repository requires approval from at least one member of
# the core engineering leads team. This is the catch-all rule and applies to
# any path not matched by a more specific rule below.
#
# @your-org/engineering-leads must include the tech lead and one senior engineer.
# Minimum team size: 2. Maximum: 6. Reviewed and updated quarterly.

*   @your-org/engineering-leads

# =============================================================================
# SAFETY-CRITICAL MODULES
# =============================================================================
# Files in these directories implement or directly support safety-critical
# functionality as defined in the System Safety Plan (SSP-001).
#
# Changes require approval from BOTH the safety engineering team AND a
# software quality assurance representative. Two separate reviews are needed
# in addition to the standard 2-approver requirement, because CODEOWNERS
# review counts as one of the required approvals.
#
# Do not add contributors to these teams without completing the safety
# onboarding checklist (docs/safety/onboarding-checklist.md).

# Safety-critical core logic
src/safety/         @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/software-qa

# Actuator control and hardware interface layer
# Changes here require hardware-in-the-loop (HIL) test evidence in the PR.
src/actuators/      @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/hardware-leads

# Fault detection and system monitoring
src/fault-monitor/  @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/software-qa

# Watchdog and failsafe implementations
src/watchdog/       @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/software-qa

# Communication interfaces to safety-critical external systems
src/interfaces/     @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/software-qa

# =============================================================================
# TEST INFRASTRUCTURE
# =============================================================================
# All test files and coverage configuration. Changes here can affect the
# validity of certification test evidence.
#
# Requires approval from QA leads to ensure test completeness and traceability
# to requirements are maintained.

# All test directories
tests/              @your-org/software-qa @your-org/engineering-leads

# Coverage thresholds and configuration
coverage/           @your-org/software-qa

# Test fixtures and mock data (especially safety-critical scenario mocks)
tests/fixtures/     @your-org/software-qa @your-org/safety-engineers

# Integration test harness
tests/integration/  @your-org/software-qa @your-org/hardware-leads

# =============================================================================
# DOCUMENTATION
# =============================================================================
# Certification and compliance documentation must be reviewed by the quality
# assurance team. General documentation requires engineering leads sign-off.

# All documentation
docs/               @your-org/engineering-leads

# Certification evidence and compliance documentation
# Changes here require QA lead AND a project manager (PM) approval.
docs/certification-automation/  @your-org/software-qa @your-org/project-managers

# Safety documentation (hazard analysis, FMEA, SSP)
docs/safety/        @your-org/safety-engineers @your-org/software-qa

# Architecture decision records
docs/adr/           @your-org/engineering-leads

# =============================================================================
# CI/CD AND GITHUB CONFIGURATION
# =============================================================================
# Changes to GitHub Actions workflows, branch protection configuration, and
# other CI/CD infrastructure affect the integrity of the certification pipeline.
# These require DevSecOps team approval to prevent unauthorized changes to
# security controls.

# All GitHub configuration (workflows, templates, CODEOWNERS itself)
.github/            @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads

# GitHub Actions workflow definitions
.github/workflows/  @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads

# Issue and PR templates
.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/  @your-org/engineering-leads
.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/  @your-org/engineering-leads

# =============================================================================
# PROJECT CONFIGURATION AND BUILD SYSTEM
# =============================================================================
# Build configuration, dependency manifests, and environment configuration.
# Changes to dependencies must be reviewed for security vulnerabilities and
# license compatibility.

# Top-level configuration directory
config/             @your-org/engineering-leads @your-org/devsecops

# Dependency manifests — reviewed for supply chain security
package.json        @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
package-lock.json   @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
requirements.txt    @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
pyproject.toml      @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
Cargo.toml          @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
Cargo.lock          @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
go.mod              @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
go.sum              @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads

# Dockerfile and container configuration
Dockerfile          @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads
docker-compose*.yml @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads

# Infrastructure as code
infra/              @your-org/devsecops @your-org/engineering-leads

# =============================================================================
# SECURITY CONFIGURATION
# =============================================================================
# Security policy, secret scanning configuration, and SAST rule definitions.
# Only the DevSecOps team may approve changes to these files.

SECURITY.md         @your-org/devsecops
.semgrepignore      @your-org/devsecops
.codeql/            @your-org/devsecops
